Arranging the Cities

The first thing to do in this data set is to seperate the City variable into two new variables. It is important to notice that in the data, the varaibles are writen in the manner city(country). We can seperate this at the into a first variable, the city, and the second variable, the country. The seperate function below will do the trick!

TB=TB%>%separate(City, c("City","Country"), sep = "\xff")

Now that we have seperated the Cities from the Countries, we can graph the Cities into a bar graph. We do this through the following funtion:

ggplot(TB, aes(City)) + geom_bar(stat = "count") + coord_flip()

Notice that the bar graph is not in ascending order. Putting the graph in ascending order will be very useful in the long run since it allows us to see in an easier manner which city has the most buildings.

Citynumber=TB%>%group_by(City) %>% summarise(count=length(City))

Now that we have grouped the Cities, lets arrange this data in ascending order. Notice in the last function we assigned the group to the label Cityplot. Now when we arrange the data, we can only arrange the data set of the new Cityplot label we created.

ggplot(Citynumber,aes(x=reorder(City,count),y=count))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ coord_flip()

There we go! Now we see that Dubai has the most buildings. Just for fun, lets add some color!

ggplot(Citynumber,aes(x=reorder(City,count),y=count))+geom_bar(stat="identity",fill="Red")+ coord_flip()

Mean Height

Now lets try to find the mean of the buildings in each city. We first do this by grouping the cities with the Height. It is important to recognize that the label is currently Height..ft. for the building height in feet. To make this easy, lets just call it HeightFeet

TB=rename(TB, HeightFeet=Height..ft.)

This column is now labeled HeightFeet.

TB%>%group_by(City)

As you can see however, for some reason our HeightFeet variables are listed as factors. The reason behind this is due to the fact that the data set contained values with commas in them. This is a common mistake for R aparently and will cause numbers like 1,000 to turn into a factor. Factors cannot have the mean computed since they are on a nominal scale. We need to change the this from a factor to a integer or numeric value. If we try to compute the mean now, we will only get back a NA.

So this line of code not only has to convert the factor to a numerical, but must also take into account the numbers without the commas. To do this, we use the as.numerical() function combined with the gsub() function. This allows us to first turn the numbers with commas into numbers without commas and then assign them as a numerical value.

TB$HeightFeet <- as.numeric(gsub(",","",TB$HeightFeet))

Now that we have the Height Feet properly converted into means, lets graph our data by grouping them into cities in a descending order.

TB%>%group_by(City)%>%
  summarise(Mean.Height=round(mean(HeightFeet),2))%>%ggplot(aes(x=reorder(City,Mean.Height),y=Mean.Height))+geom_point() +xlab("")+coord_flip()

Arranging the Countries

Now that we have already arranged the cities on a bar graph with the number of buildings they have, lets do the same thing but this time with the cournties. We have already separated the Countried from the data set in a previous funtion, so we do not have to do that again. Lets group the by the country!

Countrynumber=TB%>%group_by(Country) %>% summarise(count=length(Country))

Now that we have grouped by the country number and saved this as Countrynumber we can check on how our table looks after grouping by the country.

head(Countrynumber)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##   Country count
##     <chr> <int>
## 1    (AE)    22
## 2    (AU)     1
## 3    (CN)    42
## 4    (GB)     1
## 5    (KR)     1
## 6    (KW)     1

As you can see, we now have the country as well as the number of cities in that country as our table. All we have to do to graph them is to use ggplot2 now!

ggplot(Countrynumber,aes(x=reorder(Country,count),y=count))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ coord_flip()

As you can see we now have successfully graphed the Countried in order of the number of buildings they contain. We can clearly see that (CN) contains the most buildings from our list What is CN you ask? Good question! Country codes like this are sometimes confusing and hard to understand. We can use the countrycode package to fix this problem. First download the package with:

library(countrycode)

Now that we have the package, we can use it to convert our country codes into the proper country names. We use iso2c as the origin due to the fact that the country codes we currently see on our dataset are the two digit international standards codes. Country.name is used as the destination since we would like to see the entire name of the country our code is referring to. We also use a gsub again in order to get rid of the () parenthesis around our country codes. This allows the country code function to only read the country codes themselves and not the perenthesis.

Countrynumber$Country<-countrycode(gsub("\\(|\\)","",Countrynumber$Country),"iso2c","country.name")

Great! Now that we have converted the country codes into the country names, lets try graphing once more.

ggplot(Countrynumber,aes(x=reorder(Country,count),y=count))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ coord_flip()

As we can see, (CN) turned out to be China. Lets make our bargraph colorful for one last touch.

ggplot(Countrynumber,aes(x=reorder(Country,count),y=count))+geom_bar(stat="identity",fill="red")+ coord_flip()

Mean Height of Country

We already did the mean height of buildings in each city, but now lets instead do that with the countries in a bar graph.

TB%>%group_by(Country)%>%
  summarise(Mean.Height=round(mean(HeightFeet),2))%>%ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Country,Mean.Height),y=Mean.Height))+geom_bar(stat="identity",fill="Blue")+coord_flip()+xlab("")+coord_flip()

Mean Heights of Use

This time, we will look at the mean heights based on the intended use of a building.

TB%>%group_by(Use)%>%
  summarise(Mean.Height=round(mean(HeightFeet),2))%>%ggplot(aes(x=reorder(Use,Mean.Height),y=Mean.Height),)+geom_bar(stat="identity")+coord_flip() +xlab("")
